The right-wing populists in Austria are winning, they have 29 percent overall
According to preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria have brought about a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current grand coalition, as well as a marked strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly heavy losses.
On the other hand, the election leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthia Governor Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the national political scene.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain the country's leading political force with 29.8 percent of the vote, but compared to the 2006 elections they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent lost almost nine percent of the vote, finished even worse.
This is the worst result of the two major parties since the war, and the result is literally catastrophic, especially for the People's Party, which called early elections.
Back in early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
But the voters clearly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculation about the possible resignation of the party leader and current Vice Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer was pronounced.
Observers believe this could happen as soon as Monday, at the extraordinary party leadership council.
Such a development would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP grand coalition.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free (FPÖ) reportedly gaining 18 percent and the BZÖ 11 percent of the vote - the Socialists at the same time expressed fear of a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at that time, the FPÖ was still unified, the BZÖ split from it in 2005) on a joint government, which even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already said he was ready to work with any party and that he planned to return to Vienna on the national political scene, is apparently betting on this development.
The last party to gain access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
Clearly, no other party has crossed the four percent threshold and entered parliament.
Schwarzenberg: Relations with India at risk of cooling
If the problem of the Czech researchers accused in India of illegally collecting cockroaches is not resolved, the Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg said, the result would be a certain cooling of Czech-Indian relations.
The minister said this today in New York after meeting with his Indian counterpart Pranab Mukherjee.
"If the problem is not solved, then yes, a certain cooling-off would happen", he said after the meeting, which was organised on a Czech initiative.
Mukherjee said, coming out of the talks, that the executive could hardly intervene in judicial matters.
He did, however, mention that in the case of Petr Švácha, who was cleared of the charges and fined, the central government could negotiate with the local government, the Darjeling, as the case was placed under its jurisdiction.
"His problem could be solved", said the minister.
According to Mukherjee, the best solution for Emil Kučera, who was sentenced to three years in prison, would be to appeal to a higher court.
He said he could then apply for bail and await trial in freedom.
Schwarzenberg confirmed that his partner had expressed the same view during the talks.
"He advises appealing to a higher court, after which he could be pardoned", says the Czech diplomat.
The only way the Czech side can intervene in this case is to provide the convicts with 'competent legal support', the Indian minister said.
He also said that such assistance had already been given by India.
"We wish above all to maintain the best relations with India, which have a long tradition.
The Indians also recognize this", Schwarzenberg said.
At the same time, as he told ČTK, he stressed to his partner that the Czech Republic attached great importance to the problem of Czech entomology.
'We consider the imprisonment and indictment of these Czech researchers a big mistake,' he said.
