"I have already received a fairly large number of promises", he merely states.
A Czech referee in the fight for the seabed
He approaches an electronic wall map, showing Australia and the surrounding marine areas.
But he is not interested in the continent, but in a little dot lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
This area is as big as the continent itself", says Italian jurist Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the 30-member team of the UN Division for Oceans and the Law of the Sea.
Its head, the director of the division, Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and the completion from time to time.
The atmosphere is one of hard work and enthusiasm.
The seabed hides a world that is so far unknown and rich in natural resources.
It may contain oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also unknown living organisms that may hold the key to the development of a drug for cancer.
A depth wider than the dry land
The coastal states have now begun to crave new underwater territories with impassioned fervor.
They are exercising their rights under a UN convention, which was agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of a given country.
The latter can, according to the convention, claim exclusive claim to all the resources of the continental shelf.
'To simplify, the continental shelf is the part of the seabed and its subsoil which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles which constitute the exclusive economic zone", explains Mikulka.
The request that the country in question makes to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation, based on many costly surveys and surveys.
It is the result of years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the Commission with legal and scientific and technical assistance.
The Commission has so far dealt with five applications from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far only the last three countries have been successful", adds Mikulka.
Australia's success, as the first to significantly expand its underwater possessions, has recently received worldwide attention.
New Zealand has also gained territory - the area of the seabed, which the commission estimated last week to be 1.6 million square kilometers, is six times the size of the country.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefits they expect to derive from the exploitation of the seabed in the future will be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will apply in turn.
They can do so within 10 years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
Where the continental shelf ends, the ocean floor begins, a conventionally declared "common heritage of mankind".
There is no longer any state in an exclusive position.
The right to extract in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"But let us not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike", says Mikulka, exaggerating, adding that "its areas are clearly defined and their regime is based on a contract".
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed is now also owned by the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern Bloc countries in the framework of the joint organization Interoceanmetal.
It was granted the status of so-called 'pioneer investor' under the Convention in 1991, along with investors from a few other States.
It has the right to mine in the ClarionClipperton area in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area envisaged by the investor is slightly larger than the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is rough, it's like a replica of the Tatra Mountains underwater.
"It is possible to mine in an area of 75,000 square kilometres.
The area is rich in polymetallic concretes containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese", says another lawyer, Ind Pakshi Rajan.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, gives an example of this.
It reminds me of a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoem, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
