Organisers report increasing number of bookings
This should be a good winter for German travel agencies:
In terms of bookings for the coming months, according to one study, the turnover increased significantly compared to the previous year - for the winter season, even by more than 30 percent.
Despite the weak economic outlook, the thirst for travel among Germans remains insatiable, according to the study.
As for winter bookings, travel agencies saw a turnover of more than 31 percent compared to the same period last year, the German Federation of Travel Agencies (DRV) said in Berlin on Monday.
According to the survey by the GfK market research institute, increasing booking figures already dominate the autumn months.
The sales figure would thus have risen to about 11 percent more than in 2007, the DRV said.
The sources of these results are figures from GfK, which analyses monthly booking data from 1200 travel agencies and makes estimates for the overall market.
Travel bookings made since the end of August 2008 would be recorded there.
The low dollar value would make travel to the United States particularly popular, the VDR said.
There, the increase in reservations would amount to about one third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey, Greece and our country would be particularly popular destinations for Germans.
The demand for organised trips is particularly high, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
In view of the rising prices of energy and food, the costs here would be "easier to calculate for the customer than for an individually arranged trip".
Consumers can save money with discounts on advance bookings or All Inclusive offers, Laepple said.
The summer months were also very limited, so sales figures will again increase compared to last year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who took a trip fell compared to the previous year.
