Turkey is broadening its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey thought of joining the European Union, European powers were eager to invade its hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 paces from Asia, lies one of the finest relics of his fallen imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha Railway Station was designed in a neo-renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the guides tell us.
The monument is arranged at the bottom of the platforms, with observation towers at each corner, like some German provincial town halls.
The rocks are dirty.
The whole building is in ruins.
But once inside the arched ticket office, we have no doubt about the greatness of the enterprise, which represents a gateway to the West.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German association, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which was lagging behind in the game of imperialism, wanted to realize its medieval ambitions of domination with this railway that reaches Damascus, Baghdad and the land better known as Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperialist ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, brought about by the icy frontiers of the Cold War, is over.
The British and Imperial forces advanced beyond Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof.
Turkish sources say this is sabotage.
Since then, it has been slowly falling into ruin, engulfed in the maze of history.
But today, the railway crossing to Anatolia and all the eastern points, at least symbolically, serves to underline Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, brought about by the icy borders of the Cold War
Now it is time for a new policy of engagement.
The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To judge the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded a sleeping car heading to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit Turkish AKP MP Suat Kiniklioglu, one of the foreign policy experts.
The next morning, after a 10.5-hour journey, rocking on noisy rails with a rhythm reminiscent of the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived in the Turkish capital - presented as a new city of a new century-old state, turning its back on its German past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents an example of a change in the Turkish consensus.
He was suspicious of the West, and Washington in particular.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure, specifically built of stone and steel, in a developing neighborhood, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and many bakeries where middle managers in suits and ties - men and women - meet for morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
Suit, tie, and he even has a Black Berry.
"The aim of this foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its own country.
Now she has to look east and west at the same time.
Neither of them were.
She had to do both.
But at a certain point, I asked if Turkey should choose.
"Turkey", he said, "doesn't want to have to choose between the two".
He then pointed out an aspect that almost everyone I spoke to has memorized: the Turkish railway goes not only to the Middle East but also to the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, so it is as much an advantage for Europe and the United States as it is for Turkey itself.
With Turkey's integration, the message seems to be a Europe travelling metaphorically on the tracks to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpasha station, after another sleepless night, I thought back to these two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who watched the construction of this building 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to see that European ambitions in the Middle East could, to a large extent, be in the hands of Turkey.
As I waited at the terminal, the ferry across the Bosphorus, I remembered the time when Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
At least there is no longer any doubt about the continent that could claim this fascinating country.
