The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, especially bees.
A Japanese company has created a robot that mimics the flight of bees to prevent accidents.
It's called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, and it's the first step toward collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technology Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the general manager of public relations for technology and brand management research and development, the BR23C represents the rise of Nissan's safety shield.
This robot will allow the brand's vehicles to prevent collisions.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But most important are the bees' compound eyes, which can see in an angle of over 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing them to fly uninterrupted within their own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles within a two-meter radius, calculates the distance to the object, and immediately sends a signal to the microprocessor to avoid the obstacle.
"The minute it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by forking its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid a collision.
The biggest difference from any other system in existence is that the escape maneuver is completely instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Movement Laboratory and lead engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned up or down or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it to do, not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid obstacles.
"Every second this device has to process information and act on that data.
It doesn't need to retain information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, which is why it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
It may be surprising, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes".
This represents the first car to develop new instantaneous collision avoidance technologies, a technology that will be introduced in production cars in about ten years after Nissan.
The robot runs on lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and longer lasting than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be to adapt this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
