Morgan Stanley is opening up its capital to MUFG.
Morgan Stanley has announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan's largest bank, into its roundtable, which will pay out $9 billion to take 21% of its capital, a news welcomed by a sharp drop in its stock price.
A week after unveiling a provisional agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common stock at a price of $25.25 per share, for a total of $3 billion.
The price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional USD 6 billion in the acquisition of convertible bonds with a 10% yield and a conversion price of USD 31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, which is 28% above its current price.
Morgan Stanley's share, however, was down 6.79% to $23.07 at around 5pm GMT.
"This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to bank holding status", said John Mack, the group's US chief executive.
Morgan Stanley passed this new charter last week, which should allow it to diversify its operations but bring it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to take a much more cautious approach than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been modified in recent days: on Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago", explained Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG in Tokyo, "we thought that the participation would be entirely made up of common shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimise the risks and cover ourselves".
On the basis of the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley shares 7% below their book value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of earnings per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into ordinary shares within one year if the latter are traded more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at about USD 47, for a given period.
