Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Rebuild the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he was the third to vote on a draft new constitution.
Mission accomplished, with 64% of voters voting 'yes' in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the vote.
According to these results, the "no" vote was 28%, 7% of the votes were void and 0.7% were white.
For the draft constitution to pass, he had to get half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two exit polls and a count by a non-governmental organization showed a large "yes" victory, with between 63% and 70% voting.
Rafael Correa had claimed victory in the night from Sunday to Monday for his draft Constitution.
"The Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly", he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometres southwest of Quito.
As a matter of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was conducted in a calm manner according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, was on a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" advocated by the president.
The draft constitution devotes the state's power over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives mainly on the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign currency sent by its emigrants.
The bill, which was introduced by Correa in 2006, also gives the head of state greater powers, allowing him to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and run for another term in February 2009.
The Constitution also reinforces the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to implement in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Ecuadorian base as a launching point for US anti-drug operations.
