The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions who were held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
The hostages, who appeared to be in good condition, arrived at about 3:30 p.m. on a special plane at the al-Maza military base, which is adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, unable to speak to the press, by helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, said Egypt's Tourism Minister, Zoheir Garanna, on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been rocked from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous agency, which organises the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces, accompanied by two helicopters, launched the attack in the night just before dawn.
"There was a gun battle, and half the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled", said the official, who asked not to be identified.
He said that a total of 150 Egyptian special forces from the Lightning unit had been sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by Italian secret agents and special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our intelligence and special forces", he said, without elaborating.
He also denied that a ransom could be paid.
The day before, the Sudanese army said it had intercepted a 4x4 vehicle carrying the kidnappers during a patrol, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
