Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux countries are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, the first European bank to be in difficulty following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalising it.
This weekend the Belgian, Luxembourgish and Dutch governments reached agreement at the highest level on this matter, also using the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
The first major crisis in the euro area in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been escalating for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three countries will buy back almost half (up to 49%) of the bank's capital in each country.
The Bank will undoubtedly sell some of its holdings, including, first of all, the mainly insurance business which it acquired last year from the Dutch company ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares began a dizzying fall, and in the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis were already revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company's stock fell 12 percent, to its lowest level in 14 years.
Since January, the stock has fallen by more than two-thirds of its value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's management, is not realistic.
The company's management blames the uncertainty on the other side of the Atlantic, in connection with the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout plan, for the fall in Fortis shares.
On Monday, the paper had already seen a slight rise.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers but has not yet received a proposal on the substance.
The Belgian government has previously announced that investors should not worry, they will not lose their money.
No panic was felt among the bank's clientele and no branch was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate based on information about his purchases of medication.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
'There are data protection schemes which require the use of information on prescription medicines in all cases to be subject to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, or it's like handing a chicken coop to a fox", said Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescriptions for medications.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the capital insurance in case of damage depend on the health condition of the customer who presents himself, and if they consider the risk too great, they do not even insure him.
In the past, they would send candidates for medical examination, and they would only sign insurance contracts with them after they had read the results.
In the last ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he can easily obtain from pharmacies data on the person's purchases of medicines in the last 18 months.
For example, if that person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of this programme in circulation, some of which determine a risk factor at the same time, so there is little left for the insurer to do but paperwork, but there may still be some minor problems.
One of the disadvantages of this program is that a drug can be used for different purposes, for example, some mixtures can be used for migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers to be an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in research and data analysis, and they have to ask the patient's permission before they can collect the necessary information from the pharmacy.
Now they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their past transgressions.
Recently, some companies have also processed laboratory test results and linked them to data on drug use, thus being able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time it is becoming increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to broaden the scope of the authorities' scrutiny of companies specialising in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard recognises that this is not enough and has therefore developed his programme even further, which would make the transfer of data subject's exclusive consent conditional.
It is another matter whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
So, in the end, chickens depend on the kindness of the fox.
