The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
As the EU and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other issues, largely global.
Today there will also be a France-India summit, where cooperation on atomic energy will be the main topic.
The European Union recognises that India is a major emerging democratic power which should be given a wider say in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi's candidacy for permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
The Commission has not yet decided on the date of the meeting.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the European Union, together with Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Foreign Minister Javier Solana, welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and agreed that within five years they would double their trade, which would mean an increase of more than 100 billion euros.
This does not seem too ambitious, considering that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion.
In this respect, they have harmonized legally the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil aviation, which will also allow air trade to grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009 at the latest.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's largest trading partner, and New Delhi, the EU's ninth largest trading partner.
The summit focused on global issues.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as were all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a UN conference on the subject was mentioned.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle was also called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed its commitment to the energy and climate agenda, including its aim to reduce its emissions of toxic substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the fact that a global market should be reached at the climate conference next year, and greenhouse gas emissions should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wanted to prevent food prices from rising and supported the convening of an international working meeting to examine the financial crisis.
